    {
      "key": "fc9b743e-20a1-4932-81b3-004a10011ede",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_4\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Watch the video on level 1 together as a class. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> What does a music producer do?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Students will understand that a producer is someone who puts all of the pieces of the music together. They will  move and work on functions with chunks of music to make it sound great.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g317fe39f44b_0_382\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Read the instructions to level 2 together as a class. Guide students to notice the repetition of the play together block. Make a connection to the activity in the warm up and encourage students to consider the use of a function in place of the repeated code.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br />Teacher Tip: You can see an overview of the student responses on the level if you’re signed in as a teacher with the lesson assigned to a section.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_77\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Read the instructions to level 3 together as a class. Guide students to notice the new function blocks. Make a connection to the activity in the warm up and encourage students to consider how a function might work.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br />Teacher Tip: You can see an overview of the student responses on the level if you’re signed in as a teacher with the lesson assigned to a section.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_98\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Read the instructions on each panel together as a class. This will prepare students to code their own functions in the next levels. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br />Teacher Tip: Focus on how functions make code more efficient. It is easier to change code that’s in a function, it keeps your code cleaner and easier to read.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g317fe39f44b_0_398\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Read the instructions for each level and try to complete the code. Press the Run button to try it out. If something is not quite right you will get a hint under the instructions. When you’ve successfully completed the challenge, a new message and a Continue button will appear. Click Continue to move to the next level and move at your speed. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Circulate:</strong> Encourage students to read the instructions and hints on each level as you circulate. Ask guiding questions to support students if they get stuck.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_131\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Level 10 is an opportunity to check for understanding in the class.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_148\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <strong>Transition:</strong> Have students spend the remainder of the class time using what they’ve learned to create their own music. The instructions include some suggestions for what their project should include.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fc9b743e-20a1-4932-81b3-004a10011ede",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eb3dbace-f6fe-46cd-8e5a-0901a1957364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2cd93f46-82cb-4a99-a539-55eb1dfd69f9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g317fe39f44b_0_468\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Review the objectives of the lesson. Have students show a thumbs up/down/sideways to reflect on whether they reached each objective.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g317fe39f44b_0_489\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Have students set up for a quick Turn & Talk to reexamine the Question of the Day. Some supportive leading questions might be: Why do we use functions instead of rewriting out every single line of code? If you were a computer could you read a short paragraph or a long story more quickly? What if we want to make a change to the code? \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Take turns listening and answering the Question of the Day. Give me a thumbs up after you both have shared your answers.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_230\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> This is an optional activity to encourage your students to share the creative music they’ve built with code. Consider adding an opportunity for students to share ‘glows and grows’ after they share their projects with each other.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2cd93f46-82cb-4a99-a539-55eb1dfd69f9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bf029be1-faa4-4a35-bd77-b0c12af7fc32"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9ea5ada-cb79-46ff-92cf-2e05ee11dd97",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g1b0012b9552_0_235\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> How can we make our programs more interactive and expressive?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Get students thinking about how they can make their programs more fun and creative by adding ways for people to interact with them. Help them imagine how cool it would be if their music changed when someone pressed a key or clicked a button, setting the stage for adding interactivity to their projects.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g1b0012b9552_0_230\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Introduce the objectives of this lesson. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Welcome to our final lesson! Today, you get to experiment with using music to set the scene of a game or a movie. We will be making our music programs more interactive by adding events.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_34\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Set students up to play Simon Says [Sounds Edition] using the instructions and example commands on the slide. Rotate the leader, Simon, for as long as time allows. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> This game works similarly to the way events work in computer programming. We were always waiting for the trigger (“Simon Says”) to tell us we should do an action. If the trigger wasn’t there, we didn’t do anything.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_52\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Finish the warm up activity with an explanation of how events can be used to make code more interactive and respond to user inputs. They will be practicing customizing and creating events in code in the next activity in Music Lab.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b9ea5ada-cb79-46ff-92cf-2e05ee11dd97",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a0111bad-4a0f-428b-9b88-50570e07a43f"
      }
    },
